Runs full CTX tooling refresh for a scaffolded project: calls `install-tools.sh` for binaries/prompts, then unconditionally overwrites a fixed mirror-set of pure-tooling files from an upstream CTX repo checkout — lint configs (`clippy.toml`, `rustfmt.toml`, `deny.toml`), check scripts under `scripts/` (`cycle_check.sh`, `machete_check.sh`, `no_allow_check.sh`, `workspace_lints_check.sh`, `rationale_check.py`), and `.claude/settings.json`. This is the single command a scaffolded project runs to catch up on CTX changes that `install-tools.sh` alone doesn't cover.

Takes an optional path to the CTX repo as `$1`, falling back to `CTX_REPO` env var, then `../CTX`; validity of that path is checked only inside `install-tools.sh`, not here. Every file in the mirror set is copied unconditionally — no diffing, no skip-if-locally-modified logic — so any local edits to these specific files are silently lost on each run.

The CLAUDE.md tool-contracts block is handled specially: rather than whole-file copy (this project's CLAUDE.md carries project-specific prose outside that block), it splices only the region between `<!-- BEGIN GENERATED tool-contracts (scripts/gen_tool_contracts.sh --write) -->` and `<!-- END GENERATED tool-contracts -->` markers, pulled from the upstream repo's own `template/CLAUDE.md`. It does not regenerate the block locally via `gen_tool_contracts.sh`, because that script's `DOCS` array is hardcoded to the CTX repo's own three docs and doesn't fit a single-CLAUDE.md project layout; marker strings must match exactly what `gen_tool_contracts.sh` in the CTX repo uses, or this fails fast. Missing markers or missing source/target files cause an immediate `FAIL` and nonzero exit.

The script copies itself (`scripts/update-template.sh`) from the upstream repo as the very last step, after all other work — intentional ordering, since Bash reads a running script incrementally and self-overwriting mid-execution isn't safe for a multi-step script.